Semilarski v. Prosecutor’s Office: the cassation of the former Vice-Mayor of Tartu will be considered on August 4
This means that the decision on it is likely to be made in early September.
The courts of the first two instances to consider the claim Semilarsky refused, but in April his cassation appeal was taken into consideration by the State Court.
On 12 December 2019 the Tartu Administrative Court returned the complaint to the applicant, as her permission was not within its jurisdiction.
The court decision stated that the complaint contained a claim for compensation for damage caused during criminal proceedings.
“The prosecutor’s office and the district court should regulate such issues,” press secretary of the Tartu courts Anette Kreitsmann told ERR earlier.
According to her, Valvo Semilarski appealed this decision to the district court, which on February 5 did not change the decision of the court of first instance.
Now the Lord will have to say his word.
According to Semilarski’s defense attorney, juror Oliver Nees, his client had been unreasonably under suspicion of bribery for about two years.
Now he demands that the prosecutor’s office refute the false allegations against him and compensate him for moral damage.
The reason for submitting the complaint to the court was the statements of the prosecutor for special cases of the Luuna District Prosecutor’s Office Margus Gross, made in October 2017, when Semilarsky, along with another then Deputy Mayor of Tartu, Artem Suvorov, was detained on suspicion of committing several crimes.
“We would like to remind you that when I was detained, the Security Police and the Prosecutor’s Office immediately organized a press conference and informed the whole Republic of Estonia that the leaders of Tartu, one of the most influential local self-government bodies, were corrupt.
These public suspicions, hanging in the air, accompanied me for about two years.
And now, when these allegations and suspicions turned out to be false, the prosecutor’s office does not want to say anything about it,” Semilarsky said in early August 2019.
According to Oliver Nyaez, at a press conference, the prosecutor went beyond the legal framework within which the prosecutor’s office should operate.
“The allegations of bribery and venality have proven to be false, but that’s not the only problem here.
The European Court of Human Rights, for example, has repeatedly stressed in its rulings on Russia, as well as on Lithuania, that at the stage of the investigation, representatives of the state should be careful when choosing words so that suspects would not be represented as criminals before sentencing.
The prosecutor’s office is also bound by the presumption of innocence, which, unfortunately, was not observed in this case against Valvo Semilarski,” Nees said.
“Semilarski’s public presentation as a serious offender and briber in circumstances where the facts underlying the suspicion of bribery are still being investigated is unacceptable, contrary to the presumption of innocence and unfair to the applicant,” the lawyer added.
According to rus.err.ee, former deputy mayor of Tartu Valvo Semilarski will not be prosecuted on charges of bribery - the criminal case against him was partially closed in July.
At the same time, the former official is being tried on charges of knowingly violating anti-corruption legislation when conducting transactions on an especially large scale.
According to the indictment, in the period from 2015 to 2017, the former deputy mayor of Tartu more than thirty times participated in the meetings of the city government in making decisions related to companies operating in Tartu, with the owners or managers of which Semilarsky actively communicated at a personal level outside working hours.
According to Gross, in all these cases, Semilarsky had personal interests, and therefore he had to withdraw from participation in decision-making.
Earlier, as rus.err.ee wrote, the prosecutor’s office has charged Semilarsky with accepting a bribe and violating anti-corruption legislation when conducting transactions on an especially large scale.
This happened in October 2016, when he was detained along with another deputy mayor Artem Suvorov (Center Party).
At the time, prosecutors and the Security Police said there was strong evidence against both vice mayors.
Both officials then resigned.
Suvorov’s case later reached a court that fully justified the policy.
The trial in the Valvo Semilarski case is still ongoing.
