The actor of the Russian series responded to the accusations of “propaganda of LGBT and feminism”
The actor of the Russian TV series “Chiki”, the creators of which were accused of “propaganda of LGBT and feminism”, responded to the claims to the film.
The authors “understood the severity of the topics raised and did not want to offend anyone,” said American Stephen Thomas Oxner in an interview with the publication “Rise”.
“It seems to me that this is a story about the power and common aspects of human life.
It has nothing to do with LGBT and feminism,” said the actor, who played the father of the boy, who dressed in women’s clothing.
He said he was “proud of the work” and did not consider it propaganda.
At the same time, the American added, he is frightened by the reaction of some people to the storyline of the series: for example, there was a case when “a man in deep drunkenness shot the set and said that all this is not true.”
“Then there were a couple of cases where we met dissatisfied locals who didn’t understand what we were doing.
But we were open, so people who first came with claims began to help us,” he concluded.
The case of the shooting, the newspaper explains, occurred in September 2019 in Kabardino-Balkaria: a drunken man attacked the car of the crew with a weapon, after which he was detained by police.
